Below is a step‐by‐step breakdown of how the target structure appears and which dictionary blocks (by index) are needed.  Then, an example assembly order is given.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1)  DESCRIPTION OF THE TARGET STRUCTURE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
•  Total Block Count:  15  
•  Overall “Layers”:   Up to about four or five layers high (counting from the red arches on the ground up to the orange triangular block).  

Layout (left to right):
•  Base Layer  
   – Five red arches in a row (all showing the arch opening from the front).  
•  Above the Left Two Arches  
   – Each has one short green block standing upright, with a tall yellow block stacked on top.  This creates two “tower”‐like columns.  
•  Center/Right Portion (“Horse” Shape)  
   – Two horizontal yellow blocks bridging across arches in the middle.  
   – Two small blue cubes perched above those yellow blocks.  
   – One horizontal green block spanning the rightmost arches at about the same height as the blue cubes.  
   – A single orange triangular block resting on top (forming the “head” or peak).  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2)  REQUIRED BLOCKS & THEIR INDICES
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

•  Red Arches (5×):  Index 1  
  (All five arches appear in the same orientation as dictionary block 1, with the arch opening facing forward.)  

•  Short Upright Green Blocks (2×):  Index 7  
  (These two match the height/orientation of the green blocks used in the “tower” bases on the left.)  

•  Horizontal Green Block (1×):  Index 9  
  (Used as the green beam or “back” spanning arches on the right.)  

•  Tall Yellow Blocks (2×):  Index 12  
  (On top of the two upright green blocks, forming the tall towers.)  

•  Horizontal Yellow Blocks (2×):  Index 11  
  (Bridging across arches in the middle to support the blue cubes.)  

•  Blue Cubes (2×):  Index 4  
  (Both cubes are the same small blue cube as shown in block 4.)  

•  Orange Triangular Block (1×):  Index 14  
  (Used at the top right as an orange triangular “roof” or peak.)  

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3)  EXAMPLE ASSEMBLY ORDER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Below is one logical way to stack them (you may vary the exact order slightly as long as lower blocks are placed first).  Use the exact block indices as given (no rotation allowed):

{
  Step1:  Move block with index 1  
  Step2:  Move block with index 1  
  Step3:  Move block with index 1  
  Step4:  Move block with index 1  
  Step5:  Move block with index 1            // Place 5 red arches in a row

  Step6:  Move block with index 7  
  Step7:  Move block with index 7            // Place two short green blocks on top of the leftmost arches

  Step8:  Move block with index 12  
  Step9:  Move block with index 12           // Stack the tall yellow blocks on those two green blocks

  Step10: Move block with index 11  
  Step11: Move block with index 11           // Lay two horizontal yellow blocks bridging arches in the middle

  Step12: Move block with index 9            // Place the horizontal green beam on the right arches

  Step13: Move block with index 4  
  Step14: Move block with index 4            // Seat both blue cubes above the yellow beams

  Step15: Move block with index 14           // Finally, top it off with the orange triangular piece
}
